            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rachel Nazari\u2019s sense of civic duty was coded into her DNA. The daughter of a stoic postal worker and a quietly passionate librarian in Madison, Wisconsin, her childhood was a study in the steady, essential rhythm of public service. She grew up believing that a well-run system was the foundation of a just society. This conviction propelled her to the University of Wisconsin for her undergraduate degree and then west to San Francisco State University for her Master's in Public Administration, drawn by the city\u2019s reputation as a dynamic, if chaotic, urban laboratory.\n\nHer early career at the San Francisco Municipal Transportation Agency (SFMTA) was a rapid ascent, moving from junior analyst to project manager. During this time, she married an Iranian-American architect, taking his name, Nazari. The marriage, though ultimately ending in an amicable divorce a decade ago, broadened her cultural horizons and deepened her empathy. The split served as a quiet turning point, solidifying her resolve to build a life on her own terms, one rooted in professional purpose. She poured her energy into her work, navigating the labyrinthine politics of urban planning with a pragmatism that masked a fierce idealism.\n\nNow, as Deputy Director of the Transit Division, Rachel\u2019s life is deeply intertwined with the city\u2019s pulse. She lives in a small but bright apartment in NoPa (North of the Panhandle), a location she chose for its direct access to the 5-Fulton bus line. Her 3.5-mile commute is a daily field study; she observes rider patterns, notes delays, and feels the frustrations and triumphs of the system she helps manage. Her social circle is small and tight-knit, mostly colleagues and friends from graduate school who share her commitment to public life.\n\nRachel\u2019s dream isn\u2019t a bigger title, but a tangible legacy: she wants to be instrumental in launching the next-generation Muni fleet and see a major Bus Rapid Transit corridor fully completed before she retires. Her hope is for a San Francisco where public transit is so reliable and efficient that it becomes the undisputed first choice for everyone. For Rachel, fixing the city's transit isn't just a job; it's the ultimate expression of her upbringing and the central purpose of her life in her adopted home."
